definition.value: A quantification of the MHC component beta-2 microglobulin, typically in a blood sample. Used as progostic indicator in multiple myeloma, and diseases associated with increased cell turnover. Levels are also elevated in several benign conditions such as chronic inflammation, liver disease, renal dysfunction, some acute viral infections, and a number of malignancies, especially hematologic malignancies associated with the B-lymphocyte lineage.
quantification of the outcome of a kidney transplant

Quantification of antiphospholipid antibodies in a biological sample, usually a blood sample. Antiphospholipid antibodies include anticardiolipin antibodies (ACL), lupus anticoagulant (LAC), and anti- β 2 glycoprotein I antibodies (anti- β 2GPI).They can be an indicator of antiphospholipid syndrome
growth is measured as the difference in body height between two time points

detection or quantification of bands of immunoglobulins in blood serum or cerebrospinal fluid, usually as an indicator of central nervous system disorders such as multiple sclerosis, Lyme disease, systemic lupus erythematosus or neurosarcoidosis
measurement of the flow rate of filtered fluid through the kidney, calculated either by comparative measurements of substances in the blood and urine, or estimated from a blood test
quantification of the pattern of links between distinct units within a nervous system through neuroimaging techniques such a MRI
quantification of the rate of hydrolysis of aspirin in blood as an indicator of the therapeutic effectiveness of aspirin

A measure of the corneal thickness (CCT). This can be measured by contact e.g. ultrasound, confocal microscpy or non contact methods e.g. biometry. Reduced central corneal thickness is used as an indicator for glaucoma.
A cell line which is a model for neuroblastoma.
A cell line which is a model for breast adenocarcinoma.
A cell line used as model for hepatocellular carcinoma.
A cell line used as a model for cervical adenocarcinoma.
A cell line which is used as a model for cervical carcinoma.
An established epithelial cell line derived from an adenocarcinoma of human endometrial lining.
The CH12.LX B cell line derived from the murine CH12 B cell lymphoma.
Neuroectodermal cell line derived from a cerebral brain tumor.
The NTERA-2 cl.D1 cell line is a pluripotent human testicular embryonal carcinoma cell line derived by cloning the NTERA-2 cell line. Derived from metastatic site: lung
A human epithelial cell derived from subject with grade IV glioblastoma; astrocytoma.
quantification of an individual's occupation, both in terms of employment vs unemployment and in terms of nature of employment, eg self-employment
quantification of the enzyme myeloperoxidase in the blood, for example as an indicator of coronary artery disease
measurement of the IgG antibody isotype produced by plasma cells in response to a Heliobacter pylori infection

TOV-112D is a human epithelial cell line initiated in October of 1992 from a patient with early onset ovarian cancer. The patient was of French-Canadian descent with an unknown family history of ovarian cancer.

The ectocervical Ect1/E6E7 (ATCC CRL-2614) and endocervical End1/E6E7 (ATCC CRL-2615) cell lines were established in 1996 from normal epithelial tissue taken from a premenopausal woman undergoing hysterectomy for endometriosis.
MOLT-3 is a male human malignant T-lymphoblastic cell line.
quantification of selenium in blood

quantification of copper in blood used in the diagnosis of Wilson's disease (in combination with ceruloplasmin measurement) or copper deficiences. Low levels may indicate Wilson's disease, high levels may indicate liver disease.
quantification of zinc in blood
duration of sleep, measured either via a self-reporting questionnaire, interview or through obversation in a sleep lab

quantification of some aspect of sleep quality, such as number of awakenings during a sleep interval or time taken to get to sleep. Sleep quality can be evaluated either through self-reporting, observation in a sleep lab or using a sleep monitoring device
self-reported assessment of how difficult an individual is to wake
measurement of the time at which sleep begins
the quantification of dihydroxy docosatrienoic acid, a metabolite significantly associated with increased risk of heart failure
the quantification of hydroxy-leucine, a metabolite significantly associated with increased risk of heart failure
cardiovascular disease biomarkers, such as ST2 cardiac biomarker and C-reactive protein, are used as indicators for cardiovascular disease and as predictors for therapeutic responses
amount of time, usually recorded in minutes, between going to bed and falling asleep
Established from human bone marrow stromal cells transformed by HPV-16 E6/E7.
Established from human bone marrow stromal cells transformed by HPV-16 E6/E7.

Mouse lymphocytic leukemia established from the methylcholanthrene-induced tumor in a DBA strain mouse (subline 212, 8-month-old female) in 1949; the cells were propagated by heterotransplantation into DBA/2 mice; an in-vitro suspension culture was first reported in 1966; cells are used for cytotoxicity studies.[BTO:0000702]
Murine B-lymphoma cell line. PMID: 14738152 [BTO:0001930]

quantification of allergic sensitization status, for example through measurement of allergen-specific IgE in the blood or skin reaction after puncture of skin through a droplet of allergen extract (skin prick test)
quantification of the distance between the anterior surface of the cornea and the fovea, usually measured by A-scan ultrasonography or optical coherence biometry
